Ranunculus muricatus is a species of flowering plant in the buttercup family. 
It is commonly known as prickly buttercup or spiny-fruited buttercup. 
The plant produces small yellow flowers with five petals that bloom in the spring. 
Ranunculus muricatus can grow up to 60 cm tall, and has rough textured leaves with small prickles. 
The stems and fruit are also covered in sharp bristles. 
It is predominantly found in dry or rocky habitats throughout Eurasia and Northern Africa. 
In traditional medicine, Ranunculus muricatus is believed to have anti-inflammatory and pain-relieving properties.
